MEDIUM|internal/verify/executor.go:99|generateFixes sets f.FixWarning on the failure and empty-completion paths (executor.go:90,96) but the success path (executor.go:99-100) writes f.Fix and appends attribution without resetting f.FixWarning. FixWarning round-trips through findings.json via the verify path's direct struct marshal. A finding that failed fix generation on a prior verify run, then succeeds on a re-run, ends up carrying BOTH a valid Fix and a stale fix_warning claiming the fix is absent — a contradictory record the Epic 7.3 PR consumer (named in the FixWarning doc comment) would see.|In the success branch of generateFixes, clear the warning: set f.FixWarning = "" when f.Fix is assigned. Add a test that seeds a finding with a pre-existing FixWarning, runs a succeeding scripted completer, and asserts FixWarning == "" and Fix == new value.|correctness|15|internal/verify/executor.go:88-100|claude
MEDIUM|internal/verify/executor.go:157|buildFixPrompt interpolates user/registry-controlled free text directly into the executor system prompt: ex.Persona ("You are %s, a code-fix executor..."), plus f.Problem, f.Fix, and the repo source snippet. validateExecutor never constrains Persona (no CR/LF strip, no length cap), so a persona or finding/snippet containing role-redefinition text rides into the one model whose output is written to the Fix column and destined for an automated PR action. Blast radius is bounded (registry is self-authored; output only lands in a column, not executed) hence MEDIUM not HIGH.|Constrain Persona at load (reject control chars, cap length) like Scope entries are validated, or treat it as a lookup key into known personas. At minimum strip CR/LF from Persona in buildFixPrompt. Document the snippet/finding text as an untrusted data boundary in buildFixPrompt's comment.|security|30|internal/verify/executor.go:152-166|claude
LOW|internal/verify/executor.go:70|generateFixes loops findings one at a time and blocks on each callExecutor, so wall-clock cost is the sum of all executor latencies. This is asymmetric with the adjacent skeptic phase, which deliberately uses a bounded worker pool (reg.Verify.MaxParallel, pipeline.go:210-226). On a review with many HIGH/VERIFIED findings the serial loop is materially slower with no documented rationale. Per-finding generation is the stated MVP design (Open-Q2 Option A), so this may be intentional.|Either reuse the bounded-semaphore + WaitGroup pattern around the per-finding body (writing each result to its own index to keep the in-place mutation race-free), or add a comment explaining the intentional serial design and per-finding budget.|performance|60|internal/verify/executor.go:70-101|claude
LOW|internal/verify/executor.go:108|callExecutor applies fix_timeout only when ex.TimeoutSecs is non-nil and positive; fix_timeout is nil by default and the config comment says "nil = inherit shared timeout" but nothing here inherits it, so a default executor applies NO per-call deadline. Combined with the serial loop, an unconfigured executor against a hung provider can block the entire verify run on a single finding with no aggregate ceiling.|When ex.TimeoutSecs is nil, fall back to the shared/agent default timeout (DefaultTimeoutSecs, registry config.go:24) rather than no deadline. Add a test passing nil TimeoutSecs and asserting ctx.Deadline() is set inside the completer.|correctness|30|internal/verify/executor.go:106-119|claude
LOW|internal/verify/executor.go:70|The generateFixes for-loop never checks ctx.Err() between iterations. On SIGINT/cancellation mid-run each remaining callExecutor is still entered; with a nil fix_timeout the provider call may not honor cancellation promptly, so the loop grinds through every remaining finding instead of bailing.|Add a context check at the top of the loop body (if ctx.Err() != nil { return }). Test by cancelling the context after the first call and asserting the recorder saw exactly one call for a multi-finding input.|error-handling|15|internal/verify/executor.go:70-101|claude
LOW|internal/verify/executor.go:142|readFixSnippet swallows every disp.Execute error and json.Marshal error into a bare return "" with no logging. When the harness built but a specific file read fails (finding File absent from snapshot, or end_line<1 from a negative Line), the executor silently generates a fix from finding text alone — a materially worse fix — and nothing records that context was missing, unlike the skeptic path which logs failures at debug.|Log a debug-level pipeline warning (e.g. "fix_snippet_unavailable", file:line: err) before returning "" on the disp.Execute error path, mirroring the skeptic-failure logging discipline. Assert the debug log fires when the dispatcher returns an error.|error-handling|15|internal/verify/executor.go:125-147|claude
LOW|internal/reconcile/emit.go:137|Result.JSONFindings() hand-copies fields into JSONFinding and omits FixWarning (and ClusterMerged/ClusterID). Today this is harmless because FixWarning is set only by the verify fix phase, which marshals the struct directly, and the comment instructs reconcile-time producers to leave it empty — but it is a field-addition footgun: every new omitempty field must be remembered in two serializers with no compiler help, and a future reconcile-time producer of FixWarning would silently drop it.|Build JSONFinding from Merged by struct assignment/embedding so all fields flow automatically, or add a reflection-based drift-guard test asserting JSONFindings() populates every JSONFinding field. At minimum add FixWarning to the literal.|maintainability|30|internal/reconcile/emit.go:137-159|claude
LOW|internal/registry/config.go:148|ExecutorConfig.BatchFixes is declared and accepted from YAML (batch_fixes) and passes validation, but a full grep of non-test code shows zero readers — no code path branches on it. A user setting batch_fixes: true is silently misled into thinking batching is active. The struct comment documents it as reserved for an unbuilt feature.|Remove the field until the batched path exists, or emit a load-time warning when batch_fixes is set true so the user is not misled that it does something.|maintainability|15|internal/registry/config.go:148|claude
LOW|internal/registry/config.go:413|validateExecutor checks e.Provider == "" and e.Model == "" for emptiness instead of strings.TrimSpace, inconsistent with the validateProvider/validateAgent idiom elsewhere in the file. A YAML value of provider: " " (quoted space) is non-empty, passes the missing-field check, and falls into the unknown-provider branch producing the confusing error "executor references unknown provider ' '" instead of "required field missing". Model has no whitespace guard at all, so model: " " is accepted and passed to the provider verbatim.|Use strings.TrimSpace(e.Provider) == "" and strings.TrimSpace(e.Model) == "" so a whitespace-only value reports the clear "required field missing" error, matching the rest of the file.|error-handling|15|internal/registry/config.go:413-420|claude
LOW|internal/verify/executor.go:82|The idempotency guard keys on the substring "fix by " + ex.Name inside the free-text Evidence column. ex.Name defaults to the literal "executor" (config.go:597) and is never validated against the agents map, so a reviewer agent also named "executor", or any Evidence text legitimately containing "fix by executor", silently suppresses fix generation for that finding. A Name containing the "; " separator or the prefix itself produces malformed or self-suppressing Evidence.|Make the idempotency marker structurally unambiguous (e.g. a dedicated FixedBy field on the finding rather than a substring match in free-text Evidence), or validate executor.name against the agents map and reject control chars / the "; " separator in validateExecutor.|correctness|30|internal/verify/executor.go:82 and internal/registry/config.go:597|claude
LOW|internal/verify/executor.go:66|The fix min_severity floor is resolved with the same empty-check + DefaultFixMinSeverity fallback in three places: generateFixes (executor.go:66-69), the snapshot pre-check (pipeline.go:169-171), and applyDefaults (config.go:601). On a loaded registry applyDefaults already canonicalizes it, so the two inline fallbacks are defensive dead code that exist only for in-memory test structs — a drift surface where a fix in one copy can miss the others.|Extract a single EffectiveFixMinSeverity() method on ExecutorConfig (mirroring EffectiveTimeoutSecs) and call it from both generateFixes and the pipeline pre-check, deleting the inline fallbacks.|maintainability|30|internal/verify/executor.go:66-69 and internal/verify/pipeline.go:169-179|claude
LOW|internal/verify/pipeline.go:256|Whenever reg.Executor != nil, newExecutorClient() is called to build the production client and passed into generateFixes even when zero findings meet the confidence+severity gate (all early gates are inside the loop). The snapshot-need pre-check at pipeline.go:168 went to trouble to avoid building a harness for zero-fix registries, but the client is built unconditionally, making that optimization asymmetric should llmclient.New() ever do real work (env reads, pool setup).|Construct the executor client lazily inside generateFixes after the first qualifying finding is found, or pre-scan eligibility once before constructing. Assert the seam closure is not invoked when all findings are below the gate.|maintainability|30|internal/verify/pipeline.go:251-257|claude
MEDIUM|internal/verify/executor.go:0|[Epic 7.0 AC9] Acceptance criterion not delivered: "Performance test shows <10% overhead for fix generation." No Benchmark or performance test exists in internal/verify/ measuring fix-generation overhead. CI exercises fix generation only with an injected fake completer, so the <10% overhead claim is unproven. AC9 is not in the epic's recorded IN-scope Boundaries list, so this was implicitly de-scoped, but the AC checkbox remains unsatisfied.|Add a Go benchmark (or a timing-based test) that measures runVerify wall-clock with vs without an executor configured over a representative finding set, asserting the executor phase adds <10% overhead — or formally de-scope AC9 in the epic and document why (per-finding LLM latency dominates and is provider-bound).|testing|120|Missing from: .planning/epics/completed/7.0_executor_model_fix_generation.md AC9|claude
MEDIUM|docs/registry.md:0|[Epic 7.0 AC10] Acceptance criterion partially delivered: "Cost analysis shows fix generation is cheaper than having all models suggest fixes." The cost benefit is structural (one executor model vs N reviewers each suggesting fixes) and described qualitatively in the epic Problem/Solution and CHANGELOG.md:3, but no quantitative cost-analysis artifact was produced. AC10 is not in the epic's IN-scope Boundaries list.|Produce a short cost-analysis note (docs or epic appendix) quantifying executor fix-generation cost as a fraction of total review cost (target <20% per Success Criteria), or formally de-scope AC10 and rely on the qualitative architectural argument already documented.|docs|60|Missing from: .planning/epics/completed/7.0_executor_model_fix_generation.md AC10|claude
